This is the tool you will use to turn every "loss" into a "lesson" for the Peopleâ€™s Law School. We treat a legal error like a software bug.
| Field | Description | Your Input (Example) |
|---|---|---|
| The "Bug" | What specific procedural or substantive error occurred? | I filed an affidavit, but the judge ruled it "inadmissible hearsay." |
| The "Why" | What rule was cited? Why did the system reject it? | Rule 801: I tried to testify about what a witness told me instead of getting their statement. |
| The "Patch" | How do we fix this for the next person? | Use a "Declaration under Penalty of Perjury" from the actual witness, or find a Hearsay Exception (Rule 803). |
| The "Ritual" | A mnemonic or habit to prevent this. | The "Source Check": Before filing any fact, ask: "Did I see this myself, or did I hear it?" |
ðŸ§¬ Part 3 | The Empowerment Formula
In the Peopleâ€™s Law School, we use a simple logic to determine our next move:
Action = (Rule + Fact) \times Admissibility
- Rule: What does the law say?
- Fact: What actually happened?
- Admissibility: Can the judge legally "see" it?
If any of these is zero, your Action equals zero. Our curriculum focuses on making sure no variable is left blank.
